\begin_layout Section
The Zermelo-Fraenkel System of Axioms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms give us conditions under which certain classes
 have sets corresponding to them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Null Set Axiom}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exists an object 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

 is false for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This axiom says empty class has a set corresponding to it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{The Axiom of Extensionality}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given any sets 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, if, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in E$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E=F$
\end_inset

.
 This axiom says that no class can have more than one set corresponding
 to it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{The Empty Set}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we return to the null set axiom and we see that there is exactly one
 set that corresponds to the empty class.
 We call this set the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{empty set}$
\end_inset

 and we give it the name 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{The Pair Axiom}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in E$
\end_inset

 holds if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $u=x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $u=y$
\end_inset

.
 The axiom of extensionality tells us that there is only one such 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and we express this set as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\}$
\end_inset

.
 So for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\}$
\end_inset

 is a set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Singletons}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an object.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,x\}$
\end_inset

 has the property that, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\{x,x\}$
\end_inset

 holds if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $u=x$
\end_inset

.
 This set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,x\}$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\}$
\end_inset

.
 i.e., given any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\}$
\end_inset

 is a set.
\end_layout

